#T_SP=de.tudarmstadt.ukp.dkpro.core.api.ner.type.NamedEntity|identifier|value
#Text=Abstract: In this study, we investigate the influence of control type and strain rate on the lifetime of specimens manufactured from 50CrMo4.
#Text=This influence is described by a strain rate dependent method that uses cyclic stress strain curves to correct displacement-controlled cyclic test results.
#Text=The objective of this correction is to eliminate the stress related differences between displacement-controlled cyclic test results and force-controlled cyclic test results.
#Text=The method is applied to the results of ultrasonic fatigue tests of six different combinations of heat treatment, specimen geometry (notch factor) and atmosphere.

#Text=In a statistical analysis, the corrected results show an improved agreement with test results obtained on conventional fatigue testing equipment with similar specimens: the standard deviation in combined data sets is significantly reduced (p = 4.1%).
#Text=We discuss the literature on intrinsic and extrinsic strain rate effects in carbon steels.
#Text=Keywords: ultrasonic cyclic testing; frequency effect; control type effect; strain rate effect; 50CrMo4; SAE 4150; high cycle fatigue; very high cycle fatigue; statistical analyses
#Text=Since the early days of fatigue research, stress based approaches have been used for the fatigue design of components.
#Text=This approach prevails in the high cycle fatigue (HCF) region to this day.
#Text=Models of this kind are best calibrated using stress-controlled cyclic tests.
#Text=In the 1950s and 1960s, strain-based approaches, which differentiate between elastic and plastic strain, were developed to improve predictive power in the low cycle fatigue (LCF) region [1].
#Text=Strain-based models are best calibrated using strain-controlled fatigue tests.
#Text=In the 1980s and 1990s, component failures in the gigacycle range kick-started very high cycle fatigue (VHCF) research
#Text=In VHCF fatigue initiation, no macroscopically plastic material behavior is observed, therefore stress based models are employed.
#Text=Ideally, these models should be calibrated using stress-controlled cyclic tests.
#Text=Materials testing in the VHCF region is conducted on two kinds of fundamentally different testing setups.
#Text=The first kind are conventional testing machines-e.g., resonance or servo-hydraulic testing machines-which are also used in the HCF region.
#Text=These machines are able to operate under stress control but rarely exceed testing frequencies of 200 Hz.
#Text=While some state of the art testing machines like
#Text=Rumul Gigaforte 50 reach up to 1000 Hz, typical testing frequencies range from 20 to 100 Hz.
#Text=The second kind is ultrasonic fatigue testing machines.
#Text=Ultrasonic fatigue testing machines run at 20 kHz but must be run in pulse pause mode because of a material-dependent specimen's self-heating.
#Text=They usually reach effective testing frequencies of 2 kHz.
#Text=Depending on geometry, tolerated temperature increase, material under investigation, load level and cooling equipment, the effective testing frequency varies.
#Text=Ultrasonic testing machines operate under displacement control [13].
#Text=In cyclically softening steel specimens under displacement control, notch stress amplitudes may decrease over the course of the cyclic test.
#Text=In research on low strength (ultimate tensile strength 919 MPa) cyclically softening 50CrMo4

#Text=[10], differences between the results of displacement-controlled cyclic tests conducted at about 20 kHz and the results of force-controlled cyclic tests conducted between 20 Hz and 700 Hz were observed.
#Text=Such differences have largely been attributed to a frequency or strain rate effect [6,14-19].

#Text=In research on high strength (ultimate tensile strength 1726 MPa) 50CrMo4, the observed differences between such tests were remarkably smaller, which has been attributed to a lower strain rate influence for high strength steels
#Text=The understanding of these test results without further processing is limited by the coupling between strain rate and control type.

#Text=In components testing, displacement-controlled cyclic tests are conducted to simultaneously test dozens of specimens with a single testing machine [20], which allows testing much larger numbers of specimens at a given budget.
#Text=These results should be used to design force-loaded components only after correction for control type.
#Text=[21] implementing a method for the strain rate dependent correction for control type
#Text=[10] is utilized to create control type corrected cyclic test results from displacement-controlled cyclic test results for different batches of 50CrMo4.
#Text=We show that for each batch, these corrected results show an equal or improved agreement with results of force-controlled cyclic tests in the HCF range.
#Text=In Section 2, an overview on strain rate effects in fatigue is given.
#Text=These effects at microscopic scale cause effects at macroscopic scale, for example an increase in monotonic and cyclic yield strength.
#Text=These effects are well studied for monotonic loading [44-52].
#Text=For cyclic loading, fewer studies are available [41,42,45,53].
#Text=Extrinsic effects are effects that sometimes or always accompany strain rate effects, but are at least in theory separable from intrinsic strain rate effects.
#Text=Important extrinsic effects are temperature, hydrogen and chlorine concentration in the crack tip due to diffusion, control type, testing volume and oxidation-induced crack closure.
#Text=Since cyclic deformation is the sum of a succession of monotonic deformations, it is natural to assume that qualitatively, the same effects apply for monotonic and cyclic deformations.
#Text=we first explain the much better studied monotonic effects on deformation behavior.
#Text=While the strain rate dependency is fundamentally different for some materials [54], we will focus on the description of the state of research on carbon steels.
#Text=At microscopic scale, strain rate is closely linked to the activation energy of dislocations.
#Text=For dislocations to form or move, a certain energy must be supplied locally [50].
#Text=In a given material at a given temperature and strain state, this is a stochastic process with an average rate of dislocations forming and moving per (unit) volume.
#Text=At higher strain rates, the finite dislocation velocity is not sufficient to accommodate the fixed displacement rate, leading to a higher macroscopic yield stress.
#Text=Higher strain rates influence the microscopic behavior very similarly to lower temperatures: at a given Peierls stress and a given stress state, fewer dislocations form or move.

#Text=With increasing temperature, activation energies increase, helping dislocations to move, which explains the observation of lower strain rate sensitivities of flow stresses at 800 $^{◦}$C compared to 25 $^{◦}$C
#Text=Between these temperature levels, a maximum in strain rate sensitivity of flow stress is expected due to strain aging.

#Text=Strain aging is caused by Cottrell atmospheres-carbon atoms pinned in dislocations, necessitating high (localized) forces to unpin and thereby raising the (localized) force necessary to move the dislocation.
#Text=At high strain rates, adiabatic conditions promote locally high temperatures.

#Text=These locally high temperatures promote the strongly localized formation of shear bands: in the formation of dislocations, only a portion of the expended energy is introduced into the crystal structure, another portion is converted into heat [55], which leads to a locally higher temperature because at very high strain rates, heat conduction is slow compared to heat generation.
#Text=The higher temperature again facilitates the generation of new dislocations, in which new heat is generated, leading to a cycle only broken by the removal of the source of increasing strain.
#Text=This may be a fracture event in monotonic loading or the onset of unloading in cyclic loading.
#Text=In the adiabatic regions, recrystallization may occur [56].
#Text=In cyclic loading, strongly localized temperature increase depends on load level and pulse length.
#Text=While the global increase of temperature is well controlled by pulse pause methods, true localized temperatures remain unknown to researchers.
#Text=Localized temperatures in adiabatic conditions may be computed based on a factor determining the share of energy converted into heat
#Text=This factor has been determined to be close to 100%
#Text=On the macroscopic scale, yield stress and ultimate tensile strength increase with increasing strain rate [44,50,59,60].
#Text=From a fracture mechanics point of view, fatigue is a crack growing from a pre-existing defect.
#Text=This defect may be e.g., an inclusion in the material, a scratch or in-and extrusions caused by persistent slip bands.
#Text=Crack growth rate is determined by an intrinsic crack growth curve and crack closure effects [62].
#Text=Crack growth experiments on 32CrMo4 showed no overall influence of frequency (varied between 0.02 Hz and 20 Hz, measured in the Paris range) on the overall crack growth rate [63].
#Text=This has been interpreted as absence of an influence of strain rate on the intrinsic crack growth curve [64].
#Text=To draw a generally applicable conclusion, more evidence is necessary, firstly regarding higher strain rates and secondly regarding a wider range of carbon steels.
#Text=Plasticity-induced crack closure
#Text=[62,65-70] depends on strain rate because plasticity depends on strain rate.

#Text=Kindly note that although the change in plasticity-induced crack closure is an intrinsic effect with regard to intrinsic or extrinsic strain rate effects, the intrinsic crack growth curve is the one measured without any plasticity-induced (or other) crack closure.
#Text=For small polished specimens, the influence of plasticity-induced crack closure is probably small since loads at the crack tip are below the crack growth threshold until shortly before failure.
#Text=No fundamental difference has been observed between the strain rate dependencies of deformations under cyclic compressive and cyclic tensile loads [45].
#Text=Specimens with larger critically loaded surface areas and volumes show decreased lifetimes compared to specimens with smaller critically loaded surfaces and volumes.
#Text=Ultrasonic fatigue specimens, i.e., all specimens used for very high strain rate fatigue tests, are generally small-sized.
#Text=This introduces a bias if the size effect is not accounted for.

#Text=Jeddi and Palin-Luc [15] show that size effects explain the difference in results with different strain rates for several studies [23,24,27], which implies that there is no relevant strain rate effect in these studies.
#Text=In their analysis, a model assuming that fatigue strength is inversely proportional to specimen diameter is utilized.
#Text=This model is meant to consider the effect of the critically loaded surface and volume, a consideration of the crack growth phase is not explicitly intended.
#Text=[15] conclude that for high strength steels in general, there is no relevant strain rate effect on the fatigue behavior.
#Text=Another extrinsic effect is oxide-induced crack closure
#Text=[62,65,67,69,88-91], which is caused by the following process: the outermost layer of the steel at the flanks of the crack is oxidized over time due to exposure to oxygen.
#Text=Due to the oxidation, the volume of the outermost layer of the crack is increased.
#Text=Due to the increased volume, the crack closes at higher loads.
#Text=This leads to the crack being open for a lower portion of the load cycle, which leads to the generation of fewer dislocations and therefore a lower amount of crack growth per cycle [92].

#Text=Although the usual thickness of oxide layers is only a few nanometers, at the crack flanks, the oxide layer may grow to a significant size due to continuous breaking and reforming due to fretting contact between both crack flanks [69].
#Text=Since at lower frequencies, more time passes between two cycles, the oxidation effect is stronger and the crack grows slower (less per cycle, not per time) than at higher frequencies.
#Text=This implies a longer lifetime for low frequencies compared to high frequencies in the absence of other effects.
#Text=This effect does not occur at high load ratios since the oxide layer is not sufficient to close the crack at high stresses.

#Text=Note that the oxide-induced crack closure effect does not dominate the influence of the atmosphere: the average lifetime of specimens tested in argon is longer than that of specimens tested in lab air all else being equal, Section 5.
#Text=A momentous difference has also been registered between dry air and humid air [93].
#Text=This effect has been reported to be pronounced in quenched 42CrMo4 steels
#Text=The effect has been shown to decrease with tempering, ceasing to exist in 42CrMo4 tempered at 550 $^{◦}$C for 1 h [93].

#Text=For a high hardness batch of 42CrMo4, no obvious difference has been observed in the fatigue life of specimens in high humidity air and specimens in high humidity argon, however it remains unclear if residual adsorbed oxygen in the specimens in argon may be responsible for the behavior [93].
#Text=For a 1076 MPa ultimate tensile strength batch of 41NiCrMo7-3-2 steel, slightly higher lifetimes were observed for specimens tested in dry air compared to specimens tested in humid air [94].
#Text=For 0.5% carbon steel, momentously longer lifetimes and a higher fatigue limit were observed in vacuum
#Text=For 41NiCrMo7-3-2 [96] and 100Cr6 at a high load level [97], slightly longer lifetimes were observed in vacuum compared to lab air
#Text=Specimens manufactured from 100Cr6 with artificial surface defects showed higher survival probabilities in lab air than in vacuum when tested at the same load level up to 2 × 10 9 cycles.
#Text=Crack growth was observed to accelerate with increasing humidity in argon
#Text=[98] and air
#Text=In vacuum, reduced crack growth rates were observed in comparison to lab air [101,102].
#Text=The reduced fatigue performance in humid air and argon is largely blamed on the prevention of slip reversal-a mechanism that increases lifetime-in oxidizing environments in general [103-105].
#Text=Slip reversal occurs when dislocations are moved along a slip band onto the surface of the specimen during loading and are subsequentially moved back into their old position during unloading.
#Text=This way, no damage accumulates and therefore, no contribution to failure is made.
#Text=Adsorption of oxygen may prevent the reverse movement, which makes the slip irreversible [106].
#Text=Irreversible slip bands lead to intrusions and extrusions, which may nucleate a crack.
#Text=The oxide layers on the surface may have a higher Young's modulus than the base steel.
#Text=If that's the case, for dislocations to pass the interface, an additional force must be expended.
#Text=This leads to pileups of dislocations just under the oxide layer, which promote crack initiation [105].
#Text=Aluminum shows a momentous influence of environment, however, it has been shown that the surface oxide has a lower Young's modulus than the base metal [107,108].
#Text=The environment of internal cracks may be viewed as a vacuum.
#Text=This view is supported by similar fracture surfaces

#Text=The sometimes distinct segregation of cracks initiating from the surface and cracks initiation from sub-surface with respect to the number of cycles to failure has been attributed to the difference in crack initiation times in vacuum in comparison to lab air
#Text=For a batch of JIS-SNCM439, segregation was observed to be present if tests were conducted in lab air but not if tests were conducted in vacuum
#Text=In steels, hydrogen is present to some degree, although this degree is very low in high quality steel.
#Text=Some research [111,112] suggests that VHCF failure from inclusions is connected to hydrogen, even if hydrogen concentrations are not measurable.

#Text=This may be caused by an inhomogeneous distribution of hydrogen in the specimen: hydrogen does not really follow Fick's law in its diffusion behavior but concentrates at points of high tensile stress.
#Text=At low strain rates hydrogen has a lot of time to diffuse to the crack tip, at higher strain rates it has less time because the crack tip moves faster.
#Text=The increased hydrogen concentration implies shorter lifetimes for lower strain rates.
#Text=In theory, all the hydrogen in the whole specimen diffuses to an infinitesimal small volume around the crack tip because of the stress singularity.
#Text=More on the interaction between hydrogen diffusion and plasticity may be found in [113,114].
#Text=If hydrogen is introduced into or removed from the specimen in any way during cyclic loading, this is a time dependent and therefore indirectly strain rate dependent process.
#Text=In specimens charged with hydrogen, crack growth rates increase momentously with decreasing frequencies [64].
#Text=In uncharged austenitic specimens, crack growth rates increase with decreasing frequencies, which has been attributed to non-diffusible hydrogen
#Text=In uncharged 34CrMo4 specimens, an increase of crack growth rate with decreasing frequency has not been observed, which may be due to the much higher diffusivity of hydrogen
#Text=These studies were conducted at low strain rates.

#Text=Due to the higher diffusivity, hydrogen diffusion may become more influential in carbon steels at higher strain rates, however to our knowledge, there is no experimental evidence available on this issue.
#Text=In this work, the cyclic properties of the quenched and tempered steel 50CrMo4 are investigated.
#Text=The material was provided in five batches, having different tempering states with ultimate tensile strengths s u of 919 MPa, 1096 MPa, 1170 MPa, 1475 MPa and 1726 MPa.
#Text=Its chemical compositions are given in Table 1 and tensile test results are given in Table 2.

#Text=Most data were obtained in two research projects on the influence of variable amplitude loading in the VHCF range, conducted at the Centre for Engineering Materials (MPA-IfW) and Fraunhofer LBF Darmstadt
#Text=These are all data belonging to the material batches with tensile strengths of 919 MPa, 1170 MPa, 1475 MPa and 1726 MPa.

#Text=The testing machines used therein for cyclic testing are a 20 kHz ultrasonic testing system (USP), type BOKU Vienna UFTE, a 700 Hz electromechanic test system (EMF) and a 400 Hz servo-hydraulic testing machine (VHF), type Instron Schenck
#Text=VHF 50D.
#Text=The results were obtained at testing frequencies of about 19 kHz for the USP, 700 Hz for the EMF and 20-200 Hz for the VHF.

#Text=For further validation, test data were provided by Osnabrück University of Applied Sciences [8,115], obtained at 20 kHz with an ultrasonic testing system (USPO) type BOKU Vienna and at about 95 Hz, obtained with a electromechanic resonance testing machine, type Rumul Testronic (RTTO).
#Text=The investigated material was quenched and tempered to an ultimate tensile strength of 1096 MPa.
#Text=The ultrasonic testing equipment was operated in pulse pause mode.
#Text=All tests were conducted at ambient temperature.
#Text=The load ratio was fixed to R =-1.
#Text=At load ratios of-1, no cyclic creep is observed in quenched and tempered carbon steel
#Text=Therefore, cyclic creep is ignored in this publication.
#Text=The fatigue specimen geometries are depicted in Figures 1-4.
#Text=The metallographic characterization of these specimens showed no irregularities relevant for this investigation; for more details see [5,6,10,115].
#Text=To assess the material behavior at high strain rates, fast tensile tests were conducted on a high speed tensile testing machine.
#Text=On the left hand side of Figure 5, the ultimate tensile strength results for the 919 MPa batch as well as a bi-linear approximation thereof are shown.
#Text=On the right hand side, these data are combined with data from the 1170 MPa batch and from the 1475 MPa batch.
#Text=For comparison, the stress is normalized to the particular quasi-static ultimate tensile strength, see Table 2.
#Text=All three materials show a good agreement in their relative 0.2% offset yield strength s $_{0.2}$. In the tests on the 1170 MPa batch at strain rates of about 15/s, two outliers were observed.
#Text=In a comparative metallographic examination of an outlier specimen and a non-outlying specimen, the outlier showed a significantly different microstructure.

#Text=In this investigation, the outliers are considered in the process of fitting the bi-linear curve to uphold consistency, since not all specimens were investigated with regard to their microstructure.
#Text=where # a is the strain amplitude, s a is the stress amplitude, K ′ is the cyclic hardening coefficient and n ′ is the cyclic hardening exponent.
